The '''Fatima massacre''' refers to an incident in [[Fátima, Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], where 30 prisoners were illegally detained, drugged and shot. Afterwards, their bodies were then dynamited, on August 20, 1976.<ref name=reuters>{{cite news |title=Argentine police get life term in 'dirty war' case |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=July 11, 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSN11412259 |accessdate=2009-09-19 |first=Hilary |last=Burke}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Ferguson |title=The Fatima Massacre |date=July 30, 2008 |url=http://www.truthout.org/article/the-fatima-massacre |publisher=''[[Truthout.org|truthout]]'' |accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref>
== Events ==
Shortly after four o'clock on the morning of August 20, a loud explosion woke inhabitants of Fatima. Workers at a nearby brick foundry arrived on scene and claimed they had found human remains scattered over an area of one hundred yards, presumably a result of the explosion. Almost immediately the area was fenced by soldiers. Photojournalists who had taken photos were kidnapped. The soldiers and civilian staff collected the body parts and loaded them onto a truck of the Municipality of [[Pilar, Buenos Aires|Pilar]].{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole paragraph; these are specific claims and the source doesn't provide any of these details|date=November 2015}}
According to the police, the victims were thirty people, ten women and twenty men, including some teenagers. Only five could be identified at the time. The bodies of the unidentified victims were buried in Derqui Pte Cemetery, where they were exhumed years later for identification.
The Argentine Forensic Anthropology Team was able to identify eleven more victims. One of the first was Susana Pedrini of [[Bronzel]], after whom they named a street in the center of Pilar, specifically in the square near the water tank.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for this; neither quoted source mentions this|date=November 2015}}.
Half of the victims could be identified by family and friends through the work of the Argentine Forensic Anthropology Team.
On July 11, 2008, two former Argentine police officers were sentenced to life in prison for their role in the killings.<ref name=reuters /><ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International Report 2009 - Argentina |publisher=[[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,,,ARG,4562d94e2,4a1fae02c,0.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009082709/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,,,ARG,4562d94e2,4a1fae02c,0.html |archivedate=2012-10-09 |df= }}</ref> == Identified victims == {{columns-list|colwidth=22em| * Ines Nocetti * Ramon L. Velez * Angel O. Leiva * Alberto E. Comas * Conrad Alzogaray * Daniel Argente * Joseph D. Bronzel * Susana Pedrini of Bronzel * Carmen Carnaghi * Haydee Cirullo of [[Carnaghi]] * Norma S. Fontini * Selma J. Ocampo * Horacio O. Garcia Gastelu * Carlos Raul Pargas * Raul Ricardo Herrera and * Juan Carlos Vera }}
