{{Other uses|Formal semantics (disambiguation){{!}}Formal semantics}}
In [[linguistics]], '''formal semantics''' seeks to understand [[Meaning (linguistics)|linguistic meaning]] by constructing precise mathematical models of the principles that speakers use to define relations between expressions in a [[natural language]] and the world that supports meaningful discourse.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mark Aronoff|author2=Janie Rees-Miller|title=The handbook of linguistics|year=2003|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-1-4051-0252-0}}, chapter 15: An Introduction to Formal semantics.</ref> The mathematical tools used are the confluence of [[formal logic]] and [[formal language theory]], especially [[typed lambda calculi]].

==Overview==
Linguists rarely employed formal semantics until [[Richard Montague]] showed how English (or any natural language) could be treated like a formal language.<ref>For a very readable and succinct overview of how formal semantics found its way into linguistics, please refer to ''[https://www.msu.edu/~abbottb/formal.htm The formal approach to meaning: Formal semantics and its recent developments]'' by [[Barbara Abbott]]. In: Journal of Foreign Languages (Shanghai), 119:1 (January 1999), 2–20.</ref> His contribution to linguistic semantics, which is now known as [[Montague grammar]], was the basis for further developments, like the [[categorial grammar]] of [[Bar-Hillel]] and colleagues, and the more recent [[type-logical semantics]] (or grammar) based on [[Lambek calculus]].<ref name="Moortgat1988">{{cite book|author=Michael Moortgat|title=Categorial investigations: logical and linguistic aspects of the Lambek calculus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CdFE9X_FCoC|accessdate=5 April 2011|year=1988|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-90-6765-387-9}}</ref>

Another line of inquiry, using [[linear logic]], is [[Glue semantics]], which is based on the idea of "interpretation as deduction", closely related to the "parsing as deduction" paradigm of categorial grammar.<ref name="Bunt2008">{{cite book|author=Harry Bunt|title=Computing Meaning|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nyFa5ngYThMC&pg=PA458|year=2008|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4020-5957-5|page=458|volume=3}}</ref>

[[Cognitive semantics]] emerged and developed as a reaction against formal semantics, but there have been recently several attempts at reconciling both positions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hamm|first=Fritz|last2=Kamp|first2=Hans|last3=Lambalgen|first3=Michiel van|date=2006-09-01|title=There is no opposition between Formal and Cognitive Semantics|url=https://doi.org/10.1515/TL.2006.001|journal=Theoretical Linguistics|language=en|volume=32|issue=1|pages=1–40|doi=10.1515/tl.2006.001|issn=1613-4060}}</ref>

